comments.body:
@haircommander @giuseppe PTAL - this doesn't map to my understanding of how Conmon handles waiting for the container process, but at the same time it does seem like it's not waiting for the process causing it to zombify.

I wonder if we can work around this to a degree in Podman with a pidfd on the container process - we can alter the container stop code to wait off a pidfd instead of polling the process with signal 0. That removes the polling aspect from the current stop code (attractive on its own) and should be more robust against cases like this, where Conmon isn't doing the right thing.

The point I made earlier about Podman not transitioning to Stopped also still holds. This is a case where the zombie seems to be the result of Conmon not acting properly, but there are cases where a process will get sufficiently stuck (uninterruptible I/O sleep for example) that it cannot be evicted at all, and we should try our best to recover from some cases.
